@carolfriedmanstudio Like many of us, I first experienced the magnitude of Lisa Fischer’s voice when I heard “How Can I Ease the Pain” in the Elektra days. Then we watched her stadium prowess though the years—what is there to say, really, about the “rape! murder! wail” four minutes into that now iconic Twickenham 'Gimme Shelter' clip without going all fan girl here. Then came ’Twenty Feet from Stardom’ which, if you have not seen, you must. And in her still ongoing period of artistry with the Grand Baton ensemble and the various orchestras that she collaborates with and iterations that she commands, Lisa defines artistic ascension and what it is to be a beautiful, unstoppable, ever evolving, depthful artist. I am always thrilled to see her.

The year:1988
The Artist: @kirkwhalum 
The Album(remember those?)
“And you know that”
The song: Give me your love

I love the blank background singer canvas when you’re called into a recording session and you listen to the song you get to work on for the very first time…  Hearing a vocal arrangement come to life through notes on a page or in the creators mind is one beautiful part of it and the other is a collection of personal impressions and emotional photographs that you get to breathe life into and hopefully capture the butterfly without damaging its wings….
 It’s a sacred time where you release all the worry, and you give yourself to the music…the artist and the vibration of voices…while breathing in space for the unexplainable to happen.
 You can capture this butterfly on Apple Music… There’s also vinyl available on the internet as well( Etsy, eBay etc)

  So grateful to be on this journey still… Thank You Lord
